comment:
In 3:19, Hitchens attacks Christianity for having God enslave people. On the contrary, Galatians 2:4 says, "False believers had infiltrated our ranks to spy on the freedom we have in Christ Jesus and to make us slaves."
In 7:27, Hitchens attacks Christianity for being "arrogant" because it claims that God has a plan for people. He says, "God has a plan for ME," as if this is selfish. It's the opposite. God has a plan for everyone, and we should help each other live according to this plan. Saying that God has a plan for me is not selfish; saying that God has a plan for ONLY me is selfish. Christianity says the former, not the latter. 
In 7:51, Hitchens says that Christ's sacrifice saves us "whether I want to be saved or not." That's not at all the Christian position. The Catholic position states that salvation comes initially through Baptism, but you can fall away (cf. Gal. 5:4) if you choose to neglect Christ and/or His teachings (cf. Rom. 11:22). This sounds like freedom to me!

replies: ["Did you think he was supposed to be making a formal scientific lecture ? I thought he was just answering odd questions about what thought about different topics . I just thought I 'd say I knew exactly what he meant by 'gift of life ' . If you really do want a 'giver ' then those are our parents . Are you saying that you would never use 'give/gift ' in the manner illustrated by my examples ? Do you live in an English-speaking country ? At the end of the day , I think he 's trying to come over as an ordinary 'Joe ' and he ai n't very good at it . _ '' Is the statement 'You 're obviously hallucinating '' '' _ When/where does he say that ? He does n't say it in the video or even the full 30 min ( audio-only ) interview on the Guardian website . As for your other questions - ask him , I 'm not his spokesperson . In fact , I 'm not much interested in Dawkins the man - it 's just that his thinking resonates with my own atheistic views developed over 50 years and enjoy hearing his 'take ' on the topic . He 's entitled to his own views , and to express them whenever he 's asked to ( and that 's what the interviewer asks for - his thoughts ) , but no-one should take him to be an authority on anything in which he 's not qualified .", "@ James Griffiths Ha ha , The great `` Gift '' of `` Truth '' our God and `` Father '' of all life to worship , through that of Yeshua , at Matthew 6 ; 5-15 . ... : ) )", "@ L.Ron Dow All your expressions can be phrased more accurately , for example animals and plants survive by taking in light and warmth from the sun , by breaking down the nutrients contained in food , etc etc . Strictly speaking , none of these things are ' a gift ' ; they are just factors in a survival . I suppose I was just trying to point out that for all his supposedly 'scientific ' , 'objective ' attitudes , Dawkins often uses odd metaphors and figures of speech , some of which possibly point to a vague conceptual unease with his own position . Frequently , his utterances suggest a much 'woolier ' outlook than he pretends to . For example , when he confidently states that a fellow human being is 'hallucinating ' because he 's experiencing some kind of spiritual communion , you have to ask in what capacity is he speaking . Is the statement 'You 're obviously hallucinating '' a scientific one ? Presumably not , because he has n't arrived at this conclusion through experiment ( nor could any experiment be devised to prove or disprove it either way ) . So is he talking as a psychologist ? Presumably not , because he 's not trained in that field . As a philosopher ? Possibly , but only one who is not particularly wedded to logical or analytical argument - possibly more of a mystical Wittgenstein type who believes his own maxims simply are true by virtue of them having come from his brain ? Whichever way you come at the statement , it 's difficult ( impossible ) to know exactly what he means , or how he thinks such knowledge has come into his possession . Similarly when he speaks of existence being ' a gift ' . Is he talking metaphorically ? Metaphysically ? Literally ? Or is he just uttering platitudes which he 's hoping will come across like well-thought out , philosophical propositions ?", "_ '' What sort of gift can there be , without a giver ? `` _ Anything you like as long as it 's free - and the giver can also be anything you like , living or non-living , intelligent or not intelligent , generous or not generous . Richard Dawkins speaks British English - the interviewer is British . In British colloquial English the word 'gift ' can imply anything that you have n't had to pay for , as in : The sun gives us light and warmth . Plants give us oxygen . The food we eat and the oxygen in the air we breathe together give us energy . Our clothes give us protection from the elements . A snow-capped mountain range might give us an emotional feeling of awe and beauty . A dog will give its love/obedience to its owner . Hemorrhoids give you a pain in the ass . ' E ' ( MDMA ) can give you a 'high ' ( think about this one - how does it do that ? ) Need I go on ? The point is , intelligence & intent are not necessary for gifts to be given ( unless we are talking in a legal framework ) . If you are trying to take a commonly-used colloquialism to conjure up a supreme entity then you must be desperate to validate your beliefs . I agree though that Dawkins does have a *gift* for using the wrong word at the wrong time ( there we go again ) . I 'm surprised you did n't point out that he talks about 'creation ' and then try to squeeze-in a god to be the 'creator ' - but then perhaps you know the origin of the word ."]
